enhancements by 2021, and resurface </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">over 3000 miles</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the strategic road network, in an effort to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">redress the effects of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> past underi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nvestment, as well as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">preparing for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> large increases in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> capacity, and researching and implementing solutions for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas with enduring traffic issues.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> If properly implemented, this programme may alleviate the congestion that is estimated to cost the British economy up to £14bn per annum by 2025.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many opportunities are presented for efficiencies and smarter road usage.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The government recognises the impo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rtance of local road networks in supporting the strategic network, and is providing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">£6 billion for their maintenance over the next six years. Building on this, we suggest that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">edefining the strategic road network to include key entry points and junctions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would help avoid congestion at intersections between the SRN and the local system.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The programme also offers £500 million in support of low-carbon technologies, with the aim of reducing the environmental footprint of road travel. Economies of scale in larg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e highway projects offer more opportunities to invest in environmental mitigation.  The potential spread of the managed motorways programme could deliver both cost and environmental efficiencies; the effects of this and other technological innovations are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">discussed in section 4.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In accordance with the recommendations of the Cook Report, independence from central government will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">w the Highways Agency to realise large improvements for the strategic road network, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which will be discussed in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">greater</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> detail below.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The introduction of 5-year control periods will also allow for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a much longer planning horizon by freeing the Agency from the uncertainty of the annual Budget cycle. Furthermore, regulatory pressure is expected to create efficiencies of up to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 20%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> unit costs within 5 years of implementation, translating to £600 million in savings by 2020.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Building on these plans, new funding options will also be available to the Agency.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the era of austerity, the potential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> gains from effective implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of multi-modal transport planning are relatively higher</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Integrated planning with other modes of transport is essential; for example, freight distribution centres </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and ports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have excellent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">link</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to both the strate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gic road network and the rail network.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The success of the Olympic Games in London showed that when planning for all modes is linked together there can be a significant imp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rovement in overall performance; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CH2M HILL’s work as Delivery Partner on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this proje</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ct</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">required </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the integration of water, rail and road systems for the efficient management of traffic, particularly freight. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">External multi-modal passenger information screens were deployed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, greatly streamlining travel times to and from venues. Widespread </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implementation of such a technology would be greatly beneficial to users of all forms of transport.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government is currently collating the results of a consultation on potential reforms to Inte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">grated Transport Block funding. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One area for potential impro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vement is the planning and coordination of integrated transport in the six Metropolitan Areas; in particular, the divided responsibility for road planning and investment has been detrimental in the London area. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The weighting of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> public transport and congest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needs in the funding formula is being reconsidered, and may be raised. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In accordance for our regulatory recommendations below, the establishment of a High-Level Output Specification for roads would be directly analogous to that for the rail network; a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s such, it would be relatively easy to integrate plans for both networks, particularly if the regulatory cycles for both utilities are aligned.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In recent years, travel by car has dropped somewhat in Britain, using kilometres travelled per person as a metr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ic. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Department for Transport’s forecasts acknowledge this decline, but do not appear to account for the reasons for it.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Studies show that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">decline is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">largely due to external factors, such as rising fuel prices, the cost of insurance and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">taxation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Should this trend continue, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private car </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">demand may be lower in the coming years than currently predicted by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On the other hand, r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oad freight is also sharply increasing; in conjunction with the fall in car travel, this trend may be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">connected with the steady rise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in internet shopping</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Thus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the fall in individual demand may be counterbalanced by the rise in commercial transport.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As above, integrated planning is essential to deliver the capacity for increased freight traffic.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The gover</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nment can deal with uncertainty in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">demand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forecasts through the use of a range of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forecasts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rather than a monolithic one</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also by understanding how forecasts have been produced by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">breaking down predictions into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">constituent parts. For example, an exogenous growth forecast could be based upon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changes in factors such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GDP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (for disposable income)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, population growth, employment, fuel costs and insurance costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">By understanding the assumptions behind and the signific</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ance of each of these factors, forecasts can be updated as economic indicators </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">change over time.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Department for Transport currently utilises a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">regularly updated Rail Usage Demand Database from which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forecasts of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">passenger demand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are derived</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A si</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">milar system could be established for roads.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eliability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and efficiency of travel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on the strategic road network can be improved through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the implementation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">smarter technology. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he provision of real-time information to users </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">phasing of traffic lights to minimise delays</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lead to tangible improvements in journey times. The Highways Agency is seeking to launch a workable driver information service through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">smartphones</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and GPS in 2014.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The use of laser scanners by police to record n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecessary information from traffic incidents provides an average reduction of 40 minutes in road closures. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This technology is currently being used by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">27 police forces, and further investment should prove beneficial. By the same token, investment in safety m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">easures prevents incidents and further improves the reliability of the network. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The results of the M42 managed motorway trial suggest that widespread implementation of this programme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould sharply reduce the incidence of accidents and fatalities, increase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capacity a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd decrease journey times. Additionally, emissions and noise levels are also reduced.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One aim of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he government’s current investment programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is to resurface 80% of the strategic road network by 2021, as well as carrying out other maintenance and enhancement projects.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Res</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">urfacing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reduces the amount of damage caused </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to vehicles from potholes, decreasing the number of breakdowns and improving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> eff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iciency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, the challenge of managing road space and maintaining journey time reliability during such a significant programme of investment must be addressed; as most work is already carried out at night, options for avoiding disruption are limited.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Revising the Agency’s funding cycle to a 5-year regulatory period would facilitate a constant stream of maintenance work, as opposed to the discontinuous nature of the annual budgetary cycle. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This transition also presents the opportunity to redefine the st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rategic road network to include key entry points and junctions, helping to avoid congestion at intersections between the SRN and local system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Other new technology can address environmental concerns while delivering efficiencies and reliability; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">currently, a system of ‘smart’ highways is being piloted in the Netherlands, which includes solar-powered street markings to indicate wet or icy sections of road, and windmill-powered efficient street lighting that is only active when vehicles are within a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> certain range, saving large amo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unts i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n energy costs. This project should be closely observed, and if successful and cost-effective, implemented in the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As detailed below, converting the strategic road network into a regulated utility will create a clea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r, long-term output specification for performance with well-defined standards for safety and resilience, and the Highways Agency will be held to account for failures.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The implementation of a Regulatory Asset Base (R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">AB) model is one option for increasing i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nvestment in the strategic road network,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and has been used extensively in the corporatisation of other public ass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ets in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and across Europe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Rail is the most similar sector, but it also applies to water, power and airports in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">del uses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the valuation of network assets as a basis for setting access charges, outputs and incentive structures across predetermined control periods.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Using such a structure would provide certainty of funding for the network, reducing the costs of uncertainty from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the annual budgetary cycle. Instead, longer regulatory cycles would be used, providing investment horizons of 5 years or longer.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">strategic road network</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would form the core </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of a highways</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RAB</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The model has several advantages over a PPP or PFI model; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">namely that its cost of capital is cheaper, the valuation of its assets forms a solid and consistent foundation for a sustainable price control, and a pricing cap imposed by an independent regulator provides transparency and reassurance to consumers and fi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nance providers. However, an accurate valuation of the entire SRN is likely to require a lengthy audit. Thus, an approximation will be necessary, with initial financing based on this valuation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Such an approximation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was used</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in establishing the RAB for Net</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work Rail.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As a case s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tudy, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the use of the model in restructuring Scottish Water serve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as an example of best practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with drastic increases in quality of service concurrent with a 35% decrease in operational expenditures over a 10-year period</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government-owned company, the Highways Agency will be capable of borrowing from the private sector, allowing for increased financial flexibility.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">feature of most regulatory regimes and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allows the company</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to manage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its business </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effectively over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gulatory period</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Such a reserve could also protect the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consumer by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">providing insulation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between long-term planning requirements and the shorter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">term public expenditure framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The precise method of securing a revenue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stream,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and associated financing fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r the SRN cannot be finalised until broader policy questions on road charging have been considered. We are experienced in various approaches to tolling that are used to charge road users for access to strategic highways assets: for example, the Agency may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wish to adopt systems tailored by factors such as peak time, location and vehicle emissions. The European Union mandates that electronic toll systems be compatible with those on the continent, so it may be sensible to use a ‘badge’ system such as that used</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by the French, which seamlessly integrates toll systems from all regions with no work required on the part of the road user.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If an alternative method of charging is implemented, a transition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> period of shadow tolling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is likely to be essential</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, in which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s operators for road</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> usage rather than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consumers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This payment is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">based on the num</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ber and type of vehi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cles using the road, with adjust</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ments made for lane clo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sure and safety per</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xad;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This system is useful in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> transferring</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">raffic risk </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to developers and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">operator</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">does not impair traffic levels in the same manner as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> real tolls or toll increases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allows the government to draw upon m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ultiple sources of revenue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to contri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bute to a shadow toll fund; and p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roject cost obli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gations to the public se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ctor sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tal, maintenance and operations costs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be reasonably known in advance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> guaranteed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for a particular traffic level.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the general aversion to tolling that is historically observed in the UK, it is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recomm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">endation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that Vehicle Excise Duty, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r a portion thereof,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e phased out. In the transition period, VED could be used as a source of revenue for shadow tolls, while </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">being replaced by actual tolls over a set period of time; 5 to 10 years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (one to two regulatory cycles)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> may be appropriate.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the same fashion as Network Rail, we expect that Government will set out the funding requirements for the ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">twork in a High-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Output Specification,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an outcome-based programme for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the framework. This will probably be done </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> five year periods. We expect that HA will work with the independent regulator and the government to finalise this specification. The independent regulator will determine an affordable price cap and the level of returns allowed on the RAB, and HA will set </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a planning framework, overall objectives and licensing agreements for regional operators. The operators will draw their capital from the financial markets, and provide access to road users who will pay VED, tolls, and/or analogous charges to the operators,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and taxes to the government. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> interpretation of this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> system is laid out in the diagram below.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Based on the size of the network and experience with other utilities, the use of several regional operators is recommended. A simple method of dividing the reg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ions would be to use the 13 existing HA areas. This allows for performance to be benchmarked between regions, enabling the regulator to compare unit costs and identify efficiencies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="624" height="392" alt="" /></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The World Economic Forum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s Global Competitiveness Report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> France as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the best highway operator in the world</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with the UK in twenty-fourth place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the metric used in this survey was strictly output-based, in that it relied on the opinions of business leaders regarding the quality of road infrastructure in their own country. As such, it is theoretically possible that the leading agency could be ineffi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cient in the allocation of its resources, yet still delivering a good set of outputs. By contrast, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we believe the leading agency should follow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aforementioned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> example of Scottish Water; achieving increased quality of service for road users, while delive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ring cost efficiencies from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">well implemented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> RAB offers the opportunity for both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Private sector expertise in corporatisation should be drawn on extensively during the transition.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The reformation of the Highways Agency is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">key</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the successful</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> implementation of a RAB model, and many of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">necessary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">changes specific to this issue are outlined in the previous section.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Other benefits to reform in line </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with the reco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mmendations of the Cook Report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are detailed below</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Distance from central government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> remove the HA’s focus from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">politically charged </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">high-profile local matters, specific schemes and programmes, and operational and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">methodological techniques in areas such as traffic management, information services and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reliability measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, allowing for strategic policymaking in terms of value for money, resource allocation and the customer experience.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The use of a High-Level Output Specification would provide: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">necessary pressure on the Agency to create an evidence base</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for informed asset management decisions; </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">transparency regarding long term goals and success in achieving these;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">foresight regarding capacity and maintenance needs; and</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">certainty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of policy direction and freedom from reactive political decisions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As the st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rategic road network is a natural monopoly, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">competition does not exist to drive costs down or incentivise good performance. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, regulatory pressure can fill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the gap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, providing these public goods</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has been observed in the corporatisation of other public utilities in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is recommended that this function be carried out by an entity separate from the Department for Transport which would be appropriately resourced and insulated from political p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ressures.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The removal of civil service constraints would also be beneficial to the Agency in several areas. Most importantly, if wages are improved at senior levels and performance related bonuses implemented, the Agency will be able to compete with the pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ivate sector to recruit and retain the best commercial talent.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A relaxation of bureaucratic controls would reduce wastage, and allow p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rocedural flexibility </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> improve responsiveness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to operational issues.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nternal benchmarking should be used to maintain be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">st practice.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In summary, </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government’s plans for the strategic road network have the potential to deliver great improvements in quality of service, cost efficiencies and environmental concerns, as well as laying the groundwork for intensive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reforms to the Highways Agency.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Multi-modal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">planning is essential to deliver quality of service and cost efficiencies. By moving the Agency to a similar regulatory regime to Network Rail, it will be easier to plan for both networks at once.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are sever</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al methods the government can use to add rigour to its road use demand forecasts. It is also advised that research into the ongoing decline in individual private car use be carried out.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Continuing investment into the adoption of new technologies will deliv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er safer, more environmentally friendly and more efficient roads. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The use of a Regulatory Asset Base is proven to deliver efficiencies in many public utilities, and will provide opportunities for the Highways Agency to decrease unit costs while increasing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> quality of service.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To this end, a variety of supporting reforms are recommended.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ideally, a workable long-term investment strategy and business plan for the SRN should be delivered by the end of 2014, in preparation for a transition process starting in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">early 2015. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Agency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will also need to deal with challenges and constraints</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such as skills/training and network occupancy while the annual capital expenditure on major road schemes triples over the next decade to accommodate expected growth. Many changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are expected, but with careful management and advice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Highways Agency can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ensure that the transition to a fully effective corporate body is smooth, and that the supply chain and wider industry have the capacity and capability to deliver the required l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evel of investment. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> CBI: Bold Thinking: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">A model to fund our future roads</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, 2012</span></p></body></html>